GASTON group have been realized using the same methodology. No flux corrections at the air-sea interface were used in these experiments. The main features of the present climate are reasonably well captured by both coupled models in the control simulations, although the biases are not the same. The transient CO2 simulations show a global warming, ranging between 1.6 and 2.0°C at the time of CO2 doubling (+70 years). The values, and the main geographical characteristics of climate change, are in agreement with previous studies published by other research groups, using either flux corrected or non-flux corrected models.",,"carbon dioxide; climate change; coupling; general circulation model",,,,,,"Blanke, B., Delecluse, P., Low frequency variability of the tropical Atlantic ocean simulated by a general circulation model with mixed layer physics (1993) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 23, pp. 1363-1388; Delecluse, P., Madec, G., Imbard, M., Levy, C., (1993) OPA Version 7 Ocean General Circulation Model Reference Manual, , LODYC internal report 93/05; Ducoudré, N., Laval, K., Perrier, A., SECHIBA, a new set of parameterizations of the hydrologic exchange at the land-atmosphere interface within the LMD AGCM (1993) J. Climate, 6, pp. 248-273; Dufresne, J.-L., Grandpeix, J.-Y., (1996) Raccordement des Modèles Thermodynamiques de Glace, d'Océan et d'Atmosphère, , laboratoire de météorologie dynamique, note interne 205; Filiberti, M.-A., Dufresne, J.-L., Houssais, M.-N., Imbard, M., Madec, G., (1997) Some Aspects of the Thermodynamic Ice-ocean Interaction in a Global OGCM, , European Geophysical Society, XXII General Assembly, Vienne, Autriche, 21-25 avril 1997; Fouquart, Y., Bonnel, B., Computations of solar heating of the Earth's atmosphere: A new parameterization (1980) Beitr. Phys. Atmosph., 53, pp. 35-62; Geleyn, J.F., Use of a modified Richardson number for parameterizing the effect of shallow convection (1987) J. Meteor. Soc. Japan, pp. 141-149. , Special NWP Symposium Volume; Geleyn, J.F., Hollingsworth, A., An economical analytic method for the computation of the interaction between scattering and line absorption of radiation (1979) Beit. Phys. Atmos., 52, pp. 1-16; Guilyardi, E., Madec, G., Performance of the OPA/ARPEGE-T21 global ocean-atmosphere coupled model (1997) Clim. Dyn., 13, pp. 149-165; Guilyardi, E., Madec, G., Terray, L., Déqué, M., Pontaud, M., Imbard, M., Stephenson, D., Thual, O., Simulation couplée océan, atmosphère de la variabilité du climat (1995) C. R. Acad. Sci., Paris, 320 (2 A), pp. 683-690; Houghton, J., Meira Filho, L.G., Bruce, J., Lee, H., Callender, B., Haites, E., Harris, N., Maskell, K., (1994) Climate Change 1994. Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and an Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenario, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 339 p; Houghton, J., Meira Filho, L.G., Callender, B., Harris, N., Kattenberg, A., Maskell, K., (1995) Climate Change 1995. The Science of Climate Change, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 572 p; Kuo, H.L., On formation and intensification of tropical cyclones through latent heat release by cumulus convection (1965) J. Atmos. Sci., 22, pp. 1482-1497; Levitus, S., Climatological atlas of the world ocean (1982) NOAA Professional Paper, 13. , 173 p; Louis, J.F., Tiedke, M., Geleyn, J.F., A short history of the operational PBL-parameterization at ECMWF (1982) Proceedings of ECMWF Workshop on Planetary Boundary Layer Parameterization, pp. 59-80. , 25-27 November 1981, ECMWF, Shinfield Park, Reading; Madec, G., Imbard, M., A global ocean mesh to overcome the North Pole singularity (1996) Clim. Dyn., 12, pp. 381-388; Mahfouf, J.F., Manzi, A.O., Noilhan, J., Giordani, H., Déqué, M., The land surface scheme ISBA within the Météo-France climate model ARPEGE. Part I. Implementation and preliminary results (1995) J. Climate, 8, pp. 2039-2057; Manabe, S., Smagorinsky, J., Strickler, R.F., Simulated climatology of a general circulation model with a hydrologic cycle (1965) Mon. 